To plot the centripetal force against mass, you can use the following steps:

1. Set the radius of the circle to a constant value.
2. Choose a range of values for the mass.
3. Calculate the centripetal force for each value of mass.
4. Plot the centripetal force on the y-axis and the mass on the x-axis.

The resulting graph will be a straight line with a positive slope. The slope of the graph is equal to the square of the velocity.

Here is an example of how to plot the centripetal force against mass in LaTeX:


\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{centripetal_force_mass.pdf}
\caption{Centripetal force vs. mass}
\end{figure}

\begin{equation}
F_c = \frac{mv^2}{r}
\end{equation}

where

\begin{align*}
m &= \text{mass} \\
v &= \text{velocity} \\
r &= \text{radius}
\end{align*}

In this example, the radius of the circle is set to 1 meter. The mass is varied from 1 kilogram to 10 kilograms. The resulting graph is a straight line with a positive slope of 4. This means that the square of the velocity is proportional to the mass.

\end{document}


This is just an example, and you can customize the plot to fit your specific needs. For example, you can change the range of values for the mass, or you can add labels and titles to the graph.

